WEBVTT

00:01.320 --> 00:08.720
Okay, we're rolling to Venice, and let's start off with how did the, one more thing,

00:09.780 --> 00:16.140
whenever you're talking, I shut my line down so that I don't get any interference on this

00:16.140 --> 00:19.200
end, so maybe a few seconds after you start talking before I come back on.

00:19.740 --> 00:20.120
Okay.

00:20.680 --> 00:24.620
Okay, let's start out with how did that crystal movie project get started?

00:25.820 --> 00:36.980
Well, I first began on Dark Crystal just over five years ago, and I took the idea of doing

00:36.980 --> 00:42.980
a film like this to Lou Grade, who was the man responsible for putting the Muppet Show

00:42.980 --> 00:47.700
in the air, and suggested that we do a film.

00:48.200 --> 00:52.020
He loved the idea, and he said, but why don't we do a film first with the regular Muppet

00:52.020 --> 00:52.560
Show characters?

00:53.440 --> 01:00.740
So that became the Muppet movie, but he said, you know, Grade will do the Dark Crystal also.

01:01.320 --> 01:08.840
So we started it way back then, and then I was working with Brian Fraud on this concept.

01:09.500 --> 01:14.240
We continued to work for the next few years putting Dark Crystal together.

01:18.460 --> 01:19.020
Okay.

01:21.560 --> 01:26.200
How did that, could you go into a little bit of detail of how the story went about?

01:28.600 --> 01:37.140
Well, let's see, the story of Dark Crystal came pretty much from all of the, it grew

01:37.140 --> 01:41.200
out of conversations with my daughters, probably most of all.

01:42.920 --> 01:47.860
Lisa and I were talking about the idea of doing a mythic fairy tale.

01:48.920 --> 01:54.200
We had just done the characters for Saturday Night Live, and we found that was sort of

01:54.200 --> 01:57.040
an interesting departure for us.

01:57.800 --> 02:00.780
The characters were more realistic.

02:01.340 --> 02:03.040
We used Taxi Dermas to eyes.

02:04.200 --> 02:08.600
They looked more like real living creatures, and we thought, wouldn't it be interesting

02:08.600 --> 02:13.780
to take this a little bit further so that we end up with something that actually looks

02:14.490 --> 02:18.160
like a living breathing thing and set it in a whole fantasy world?

02:18.760 --> 02:21.620
So that was kind of the challenge, was to create this entire world.

02:23.220 --> 02:26.100
And about that time I brought Brian Fraud into it.

02:27.600 --> 02:34.840
We operated for the first year on just the biggest development, knowing basically what

02:34.840 --> 02:40.280
the story was going to be about, and what I wanted to design the characters first.

02:41.500 --> 02:46.560
Then after we had the characters together, the storyline grew.

02:48.780 --> 02:57.200
Actually, I was looking for a time to actually put this story down, to write it down.

02:57.600 --> 03:03.220
I needed a couple of days clear, and I was about to fly over to England with my daughter,

03:03.220 --> 03:07.040
Cheryl, who was about 60 or 17, I guess, at the time.

03:08.220 --> 03:11.440
We got stranded at Kennedy Airport in a blizzard.

03:12.080 --> 03:18.620
We were stuck at Howard Johnson's motor lodge for two days in the blizzard of 77.

03:21.400 --> 03:24.260
During those two days, we had a wonderful time.

03:24.640 --> 03:30.860
During that time, we put the basic working story together that did become the story

03:30.860 --> 03:32.220
outline for The Dark Crystal.

03:36.380 --> 03:40.520
Okay, that's sort of a part of the fun, sort of a family affair.

03:41.720 --> 03:47.080
Yes, well, I tended to always work with my kids quite a bit, I think.

03:51.860 --> 03:56.840
Okay, just to give a little bit of a background, what types of characters or creatures

03:56.840 --> 03:58.400
inhabit the world with The Dark Crystal?

03:59.740 --> 04:05.780
Well, they're very different from anything that we've ever done.

04:06.300 --> 04:13.080
For that reason, we are not using the name Muppets in connection with this film,

04:14.720 --> 04:22.020
or even puppetry, because it's something rather different from either Muppets or Puppets,

04:22.300 --> 04:23.780
in that these are creatures.

04:24.800 --> 04:31.320
Some of the creatures are small, I can't puppet, but some of them are great, big, large things.

04:32.880 --> 04:36.120
With people inside, they weigh 75 pounds.

04:36.580 --> 04:39.840
They're bigger, there are some things that are about 10 feet tall.

04:40.620 --> 04:43.660
So we're into all kinds of different creatures.

04:44.760 --> 04:50.640
They were all designed by Brian Fraud, who's the English fantasy illustrator.

04:51.700 --> 05:00.000
Brian has done just a wonderful job of designing both creatures, their costumes, the entire world,

05:00.740 --> 05:06.340
the landscape, the cathals, all of that was designed by Brian.

05:07.300 --> 05:11.780
But it has a very different look, and it doesn't look anything like anything we've ever done before.

05:15.940 --> 05:19.260
I'll take it Brian, storyboarded the idea down in.

05:21.280 --> 05:27.500
He was doing design work, but actually we had other people doing storyboards for the whole film.

05:29.300 --> 05:29.780
Okay.

05:33.180 --> 05:36.800
Last week you talked a little bit about the design of the creatures.

05:36.980 --> 05:40.960
Could you go into that just a little bit more, possibly how

05:42.520 --> 05:44.380
they're manufactured or how they're put together?

05:46.040 --> 05:52.720
Well, the normal process and the reason that it took a number of years to accomplish this,

05:52.880 --> 05:57.340
was that Brian would do an original sketch.

05:58.820 --> 06:06.380
Then we would go to have one of our sculptors then sculpt the figure.

06:06.380 --> 06:12.080
Then we would mock it up so that we could manipulate it.

06:12.920 --> 06:15.040
Then we would try moving this thing.

06:15.340 --> 06:17.920
These things moved in different ways.

06:19.620 --> 06:21.640
We would videotape a test.

06:22.980 --> 06:27.760
Then we'd all sit around and look at the test and decide what should be done about it.

06:27.960 --> 06:30.840
Then Brian would normally redesign the character.

06:31.820 --> 06:33.560
The whole process would begin again.

06:34.220 --> 06:42.220
We would go through sometimes like five generations of the character before we ended up with what we actually shot on film.

06:44.700 --> 06:47.660
That's one of the reasons it was a long development time.

06:49.620 --> 06:59.480
Could you go back to creating all new creatures yet making them realistic enough so that when somebody looked at it and make it accept them as being a creature?

06:59.480 --> 07:00.160
Yes.

07:00.780 --> 07:06.800
The whole problem was whether or not we could design a world that the audience would believe.

07:08.040 --> 07:12.320
You would believe that this was a world with all of the depth.

07:13.980 --> 07:20.660
In our own world there are so many things that you look around and you accept a very complicated world.

07:21.860 --> 07:24.360
But all of these things have a sort of a depth to them.

07:24.380 --> 07:26.660
There's a lot of stuff behind everything.

07:29.200 --> 07:43.940
In that sense, Brian went about designing these creatures, the whole culture, the symbolism behind the different kinds of creatures and their lifestyles.

07:44.540 --> 07:51.480
We would spend a lot of time sitting around talking about what these people ate and how they ate.

07:52.300 --> 08:00.060
We would act towards each other and the kind of clothes that are evil creatures.

08:01.800 --> 08:08.440
They are skinny bony creatures and we figured they are nearly a thousand years old.

08:09.660 --> 08:14.760
They were layer upon layer upon layer of clothing and we figured they never took their clothes off.

08:15.020 --> 08:19.800
They only added a new layer on top and it was all kind of really awful.

08:19.800 --> 08:21.960
We figured it probably smelled terrible.

08:23.280 --> 08:27.940
But it was all brocade and very rich fabrics.

08:30.700 --> 08:32.460
It's that kind of thing.

08:32.760 --> 08:37.680
You go through the thinking process of what this evolution was.

08:37.940 --> 08:46.660
You do that not only for the creatures but for their environment and the places where they live.

08:49.800 --> 08:54.520
We've talked with a lot of science fiction and fantasy authors about world building concepts.

08:54.740 --> 09:01.160
They find that sometimes designing and building the world is the challenge of doing that.

09:01.160 --> 09:04.000
That is more exciting than the actual story that comes about afterwards.

09:05.200 --> 09:09.360
All of this for us kind of happened at the same time.

09:09.960 --> 09:11.700
It was kind of a joint thing.

09:18.860 --> 09:26.180
The story is very much an organic part of how these creatures are and the trouble they are in at the moment.

09:27.000 --> 09:30.200
The story begins when this world is at a point of crisis.

09:32.740 --> 09:35.200
Our story is very much part of the whole thing.

09:38.220 --> 09:38.700
Yeah.

09:41.940 --> 09:46.660
What I meant was when they're designing the world,

09:48.500 --> 09:54.880
lots of times when they get to the story afterwards they have to work very hard in order to make the story as exciting as the world is designed.

09:57.340 --> 10:00.440
I can see that as a potential hitfall.

10:01.720 --> 10:04.960
We got into things where it would be lovely.

10:05.620 --> 10:12.180
We spent a lot of time working on areas of the film that never got photographed even.

10:12.940 --> 10:16.440
We worked a great deal on what the plant life was like.

10:17.580 --> 10:22.500
We had many kinds of plants that were sort of halfway between plants and animals.

10:22.640 --> 10:25.200
We had these trees that would walk around.

10:25.760 --> 10:30.360
We had all areas of the mud that was alive.

10:31.680 --> 10:35.000
Most of that stuff did not end up in the finished film.

10:36.760 --> 10:42.440
When you are doing a story, the story has to take precedence.

10:43.020 --> 10:47.640
Lots of that stuff is also serving a useful function to the story that you're telling.

10:48.680 --> 10:50.060
It doesn't end up in the film.

10:53.760 --> 10:58.800
From our standpoint, it was very valuable to have gone through this process to know what's there.

10:59.000 --> 11:02.160
We know what's on the other side of that tree that you're not seeing.

11:03.920 --> 11:12.720
Yeah, that would make it the realism as the scene came to life for you.

11:12.840 --> 11:14.600
You'd better pass that on when you're filming this.

11:15.700 --> 11:18.020
Otherwise, you end up with just a surface.

11:18.780 --> 11:25.560
I think we have something here that has more depth to it because of the time we put into that.

