18:04.360 --> 18:07.520
also in Elstree. This film studio

18:07.520 --> 18:11.520
was about two blocks from where we were working. And I wanted to go straight

18:11.520 --> 18:15.180
from the end of the Muppet show into the great Muppet Caper.

18:15.380 --> 18:19.280
So while we were still doing that television show, we were doing the pre-production

18:19.280 --> 18:23.180
for the movie. If I

18:23.180 --> 18:26.980
decided to do that in the United States, we probably would have had to

18:26.980 --> 18:30.340
do it about eight months later.

18:34.020 --> 18:34.760
You're talking

18:34.760 --> 18:38.440
a little while about some of the scenes and how you had to work from a hole

18:38.440 --> 18:42.020
underneath the set and stuff like that. Did you have, I enjoyed reading a description

18:42.020 --> 18:46.400
of how you manipulated Kermit when you were doing

18:46.400 --> 18:49.240
the Muppet movie, the first scene in the swamp?

18:50.080 --> 18:53.400
Did you have any scenes that were as difficult as

18:54.600 --> 18:58.120
Manning, what was it, the USS Henson submarine that you were in?

18:58.820 --> 19:02.740
Well let's see, I don't think, we never had anything, it was quite that

19:04.460 --> 19:05.020
claustrophobic.

19:06.500 --> 19:10.300
I mean fortunately I'm not a claustrophobic person, so I don't

19:10.300 --> 19:12.380
mind being sprinted into a small space.

19:14.160 --> 19:17.660
But in the Muppet movie, in the great Muppet Caper,

19:18.180 --> 19:21.840
we would very often find ourselves in a situation where we were

19:21.840 --> 19:25.980
out in the real world, like riding in a

19:25.980 --> 19:29.880
taxi cab, where there might be three or four of us sort of jammed underneath

19:29.880 --> 19:34.460
where the seat would have been in a regular automobile.

19:35.720 --> 19:38.040
But since this film was all in a fantasy

19:38.040 --> 19:41.800
world, which was designed for us to operate in, we

19:41.800 --> 19:44.240
virtually never had that same kind of discomfort.

19:45.540 --> 19:49.640
So all of our sets were designed with knowing that we wanted

19:49.640 --> 19:53.900
to be able to get underneath the ground, or through

19:53.900 --> 19:57.920
a rock wall, and so all of it was designed

19:57.920 --> 20:01.720
with trap doors or areas that could be

20:01.720 --> 20:03.040
removed.

20:06.920 --> 20:08.120
Yeah, okay.

20:09.640 --> 20:13.360
The basic premise behind the story is

20:13.900 --> 20:17.320
I guess what the eternal concept between good and evil?

20:18.160 --> 20:21.240
Well it's that sort of thing, it's

20:21.240 --> 20:23.960
the basic story really relates to

20:23.960 --> 20:28.240
a young man growing up

20:29.240 --> 20:33.180
facing the world, facing the evil

20:33.180 --> 20:37.020
powers and the unknown, and conquering fear.

20:37.780 --> 20:40.820
So in that sense it's a very standard thing,

20:41.620 --> 20:44.060
standard fairy tale myth,

20:44.740 --> 20:48.440
basic story. But then on top of that I think

20:49.860 --> 20:52.100
the actual story that we're telling is

20:53.100 --> 20:55.680
interesting and has sort of its own

20:56.740 --> 20:58.840
strange variations of this world.

21:03.180 --> 21:05.900
Yeah, I'm reading Brian's book.

21:06.580 --> 21:09.180
I think people are really going to be able to get into the characters

21:09.180 --> 21:10.780
because of how well they're all developed.

21:12.720 --> 21:16.100
I hope so, yeah, but that is certainly our

21:16.100 --> 21:17.920
desire, our intent.

