for the next few years.

23:31.480 --> 23:35.320
And during that time the style of the puppet sort of came together.

23:35.320 --> 23:39.280
Then I moved up to New York and started doing guest shots on

23:40.080 --> 23:41.280
variety shows.

23:42.240 --> 23:46.240
The Jimmy Dean show, which is a country western show with our dog Rolf,

23:47.200 --> 23:51.140
we did that for three years. We did the Ed Sullivan show for a while.

23:51.460 --> 23:53.960
And about that time Sesame Street came along.

23:55.840 --> 23:59.300
Sesame Street, we're in the process of working

23:59.300 --> 24:03.200
on our 14th season right now. So that's something

24:03.200 --> 24:05.320
that is still a part of our operation here.

24:07.340 --> 24:09.580
The Muppet Show came along

24:11.060 --> 24:13.220
about like seven years ago I guess.

24:14.840 --> 24:18.700
We did the Muppet Show. We did five years of that, which was

24:18.700 --> 24:22.800
120 shows. And there's first and all of this

24:22.800 --> 24:27.080
for the recent Century Television Special. A lot of guest shots.

24:28.980 --> 24:30.300
That sort of brings us up

24:30.300 --> 24:31.960
to date I guess.

24:34.660 --> 24:35.540
I suppose

24:38.800 --> 24:41.660
I guess it's kind of funny, but wasn't

24:41.660 --> 24:43.700
Robert Beckey really put you on the map?

24:46.240 --> 24:48.960
Which one? Remember the song, Robert Beckey?

24:50.900 --> 24:54.380
Isn't that sort of it really put you on the map and grabbed a public attention?

24:54.700 --> 24:56.360
I never would have thought of that.

24:57.740 --> 25:00.400
It may have. Robert Beckey

25:01.240 --> 25:04.320
came up in the first season of

25:04.320 --> 25:08.600
Sesame Street. And I think it

25:08.600 --> 25:12.060
made it close to the top ten. Not quite all.

25:12.200 --> 25:14.460
I don't think it got up to about number ten.

25:15.380 --> 25:18.100
I don't think it got any higher than that nationally.

25:18.980 --> 25:23.100
I think probably Sesame Street itself was

25:24.580 --> 25:26.880
something that the general audience

25:26.880 --> 25:30.320
became aware of before that.

25:30.540 --> 25:33.560
But I think we were mostly known in the industry I guess.

25:35.600 --> 25:39.120
I can remember watching Sesame Street when it came out and really enjoying

25:39.120 --> 25:42.900
your work because the humor that you put into it

25:42.900 --> 25:47.020
seemed to be written on two levels. The both would laugh at one thing

25:47.020 --> 25:48.260
and the kids would laugh at another.

25:48.260 --> 25:52.080
That was a fairly conscious decision

25:52.080 --> 25:56.060
that we've always known that

25:56.060 --> 25:59.080
the television set is controlled by

25:59.080 --> 26:04.620
not only the little kids but also their parents and their older brothers and sisters.

26:06.120 --> 26:07.260
That sort of thing.

26:08.840 --> 26:12.100
Could you give a brief reason

26:12.100 --> 26:15.980
as to why you designed the Muppets rather than working with traditional puppets

26:15.980 --> 26:16.720
or marionettes?

26:18.440 --> 26:23.040
Well, let's see. I don't know.

26:23.660 --> 26:25.560
When I started,

26:27.680 --> 26:31.480
let's see. I started with no connection with any normal

26:31.480 --> 26:33.220
puppeteers or anything.

26:35.240 --> 26:40.040
So I guess not having a background in it

26:40.040 --> 26:42.860
nor knowing hardly anything about it, I started in

26:43.740 --> 26:45.320
probably a fresh direction

26:46.920 --> 26:50.300
coming mostly from just a different place I suppose.

26:52.660 --> 26:55.320
You suppose it might have been that you're working

26:55.320 --> 26:59.080
in the medium of television that caused you to use the design where you could

26:59.080 --> 27:02.600
have more, I guess, facial expression on your characters

27:02.600 --> 27:06.340
rather than as a static expression on marionettes or not? Yeah, oh certainly.

27:07.000 --> 27:11.340
Certainly. The fact that we, all of our original characters were designed just for television.

27:11.340 --> 27:14.980
We were probably one of the first people

27:14.980 --> 27:17.940
to do that because even

27:17.940 --> 27:21.540
Bert Tilstrom, whose work I had seen

27:21.540 --> 27:27.020
and probably he was likely the major influence on me, I suppose.

27:27.720 --> 27:30.680
But even his work had started before television.

27:31.640 --> 27:34.960
And so it wasn't particularly designed

27:34.960 --> 27:36.180
for the medium.

27:40.740 --> 27:41.540
Okay.

27:42.040 --> 27:44.900
When did you meet Frank Oz

27:44.900 --> 27:49.020
and form that sort of collaborative effort with him?

27:50.040 --> 27:52.340
Frank joined us about in 1960.

27:55.780 --> 27:58.820
Oh, maybe 1964 or

27:58.820 --> 28:02.240
five just before we started doing the Jimmy Dean show.

28:03.000 --> 28:04.660
He was a kid at the time.

28:07.140 --> 28:08.540
So he was with me

28:08.540 --> 28:11.040
in a lot of the early days of our development.

28:12.720 --> 28:15.040
And then as well, he started doing voices.

28:16.560 --> 28:19.380
A lot of his voice things really came into

28:20.200 --> 28:23.520
really great shape about the time we started on Sesame Street.

28:28.060 --> 28:29.780
Yeah, I think Frank's name

28:29.780 --> 28:31.780
was just highly appropriate for what he does.

28:35.080 --> 28:36.040
Speaking of voices,

28:36.860 --> 28:38.880
I know this, but this is just for the audience.

28:39.060 --> 28:42.560
Who has which voices that are really popular characters?

28:43.540 --> 28:47.100
Well, it's the Frank Oz, Fawzi Bear and Fawzi

28:47.100 --> 28:48.860
who was sort of named for Frank Oz.

28:49.120 --> 28:56.000
But Frank does Fawzi and Figgie, Animal, Sam Eagle,

28:57.760 --> 28:58.560
on the Muppet Show,

28:58.560 --> 29:02.100
on Sesame Street he does Cookie Monster, Grover,

29:03.340 --> 29:06.900
Bert, and in Dark Crystal

29:06.900 --> 29:10.120
he's doing a character named Ogre

29:11.540 --> 29:13.700
and he does the Chamberlain.

29:15.880 --> 29:19.000
So those are two of the major characters in the Dark Crystal.

29:21.060 --> 29:22.340
Say, what else?

29:22.520 --> 29:25.780
I do a character named Jen in the Dark Crystal

29:25.780 --> 29:29.980
and I was also performing one of the Skeksis, the Ritual Master.

29:30.920 --> 29:32.140
More or less an incidental character.

29:35.220 --> 29:36.960
On the Muppet Show I do Kermit,

29:39.620 --> 29:41.620
Rolf, Waldorf, the Chef,

29:43.220 --> 29:46.020
a few others like Dr. T.

29:48.000 --> 29:50.380
On Sesame Street the only characters I'm doing there

29:50.380 --> 29:54.960
are Ernie, Kermit the Frog,

29:54.960 --> 29:57.160
who occasionally works on Sesame Street still.

30:04.220 --> 30:06.180
You and Frank are about money, right?

30:06.800 --> 30:08.180
Yes, we're trying. Okay.

30:09.540 --> 30:12.820
How do you know the Muppet world?

30:14.180 --> 30:18.760
Yes, we've been doing that for a long time and it's still fun. We still have a good time doing that stuff.

30:19.500 --> 30:22.560
It comes to this, I can remember, I don't even remember

30:22.560 --> 30:26.500
where I saw this, but I thought it was on the Muppet Show because it was on, excuse me,

30:26.600 --> 30:29.740
the Sesame Street. It was a segment where the

30:29.740 --> 30:34.540
Swedish Chef was making a sandwich and the subtitles

30:34.540 --> 30:35.580
were all in Chinese.

30:36.960 --> 30:42.840
Well, that was the first time we used the Swedish Chef and that was something

30:42.840 --> 30:44.520
I'm quite sure this was

30:46.720 --> 30:49.280
on a pilot special we did for ABC

30:50.700 --> 30:52.400
many years ago. It was called Muppet Show.

30:53.700 --> 30:57.700
Okay, that was, I remember laughing so hard that I cried

30:57.700 --> 30:59.720
when I saw that. That was so hilarious.

31:01.860 --> 31:04.460
I've got to look at that too. I haven't seen that show in a long time.

31:06.080 --> 31:08.200
Okay, well, I think I've covered

31:08.960 --> 31:13.380
I have a guess here. If I was going to make a guess, I would guess that you

31:13.380 --> 31:15.760
were a computer games fan. Would I be guessing right?

31:16.920 --> 31:18.860
It's interesting, not particularly.

31:21.100 --> 31:23.580
I grew up playing a lot of games

31:25.380 --> 31:27.740
and I enjoy computer games, but I

31:27.740 --> 31:31.660
sort of never get around to doing it. I guess I have a busy life and I

31:31.660 --> 31:35.020
don't, you know, we had an Atari,

31:35.540 --> 31:39.700
we have an Atari unit at home for the kids, which I've enjoyed playing some of

31:39.700 --> 31:42.200
those games, but I haven't really gotten into it.

31:44.780 --> 31:46.360
Okay, missed my mark,

31:46.460 --> 31:50.160
what can I say? If a person was interested

31:52.280 --> 31:54.280
in doing what you do or going

31:54.280 --> 31:58.040
to work for somebody like you, what type of area would they study in,

31:58.160 --> 32:00.600
work in, do, what type of person are you looking for?

32:02.980 --> 32:06.320
Well, I don't know. It's different kinds of things. There's a performer

32:06.320 --> 32:08.920
for performers, I look for people who have

32:11.220 --> 32:13.100
a sense of humor,

32:13.560 --> 32:15.080
a sense of humor and a kind of

32:15.080 --> 32:20.520
ability of performing and focusing their performance in their

32:20.520 --> 32:24.600
hands. There's specific things one looks for in terms of

32:24.600 --> 32:25.260
puppeteering.

32:28.740 --> 32:32.640
But, you know, the whole film business

32:32.640 --> 32:34.660
right now is a very exciting time.

32:37.280 --> 32:40.060
Everybody is on the lookout for people with a lot of talent.

32:45.280 --> 32:46.400
Okay, well I'll take that

32:46.400 --> 32:49.940
plenty of your time there. Certainly do appreciate you taking time not to talk with me.

32:50.200 --> 32:54.060
Okay, good Dave. It was a pleasure. Okay, whenever we get the tapes cut together

32:54.060 --> 32:57.440
I'll send you a copy of the completed shows. Great, that would be very nice.

32:57.720 --> 33:00.340
Okay, thank you. Thank you very much Mr. Hansen. Bye-bye.

